Observation Details: To have two birds was a big suprise! Both are male, but one is dominant. I saw two different chases. Once they had both landed in the bare willow tree (S end of lake) but one immediately chased the other towards the redwoods.  At another time there was a chase towards the tree and around it, but neither landed. At various times a male landed in the tree (and both were present for a few moments), but only once (near the end of my time) did one land and linger to check out many of the sap holes (and allowed for many photos). At another time one was very skittish at the upper holes (no photo) and left quickly. They may differ is details of facial pattern (red throat breaking through black surrounding line), and in details in size/shape of red nape patch, but I will need to check through all prior photos to see if I have photos of both. Today I only photo'd one -- the dominate male (below):

Observation Details: Reported by Darian Santner to the Oregon Birding Discord, Portland area chat, and with an excellent photo of a clean RNSA individual. I arrived with Darian still on the scene as the RNSA squabbled with 2 RBSA on the cottonwoods. After about 5-10 minutes of this they split up and did not see them again before I left. Darian mentioned that the birds would squabble, break up, and begin squabbling again on the same tree as the pin below.  The individual was a male with a red throat with a cleanly demarcated black band below it. Only one red spot behind the eye on the black behind the eyes, clean red forecrown (clean black on hindcrown), red on nape, white line behind the eye. Clean white line from above the bill with a tinge of red bleeding into it behind the eye, wrapping around the red throat and black breast band. Tinge of yellow below the black breast band in the white on the underside near shoulder spur. The red behind the eye and a little in the white below the eye seems to be within range for pure per Macaulay and Sibley. For RBSA hybrid would expect to see red bleeding into the black breast band and in the black on the face and head, but everything seems to be cleanly demarcated. Ruling out YBSA hybrid with the cleaner looking barring on the back, the incomplete black border around the red throat and overall cleaner look.  Last seen here: 45.481723,-122.651812

Red-naped Sapsucker spot, SW Stellar Dr.
Observation Details: Continuing, thank you to all who posted about it! Lifer!!  Easily found in the group of trees others are reporting it in (where my marker is placed, too). Look in the deciduous trees near a dip in the trail, by a large circular concrete thing on the ground between the trail and the houses. It flies back and forth in that stand of trees, creating/feeding on/defending its sap wells.  One of the most beautiful and handsome birds I've ever seen... Brilliant red throat and forehead, stately black bib, crisp black and white stripes on face, soft red smudges on nape (my favorite part, it was beautiful to look at!), two rows of barring on the back.  It makes incredible square sap wells, unlike anything I've seen before (I'm used to the Red-breasted's perfect little circular holes). It's also extremely territorial towards all birds who approach its sap squares, actively chasing away many relentless hummingbirds and one opportunistic RCKI. However, it didn't even cast a glance at the many barking dogs or curious humans that passed by.   What an amazing bird... I couldn't get enough of its antics, and watching it as it made its squares. Sometimes it would carefully run the side of its beak up and down a branch, not as though wiping it, but as though it was sensing where to peck next, for it would then start working on a square in that spot.   Truly remarkable!!

Continuing bird. Seen very briefly as it flew from the Himalayan Cedar to another tree. I caught a glimpse of the white rump and black back before I lost it. In the tree, I spied many sapsucker holes. After waiting for a few minutes, it flew back to the Himalayan Cedar where I took some photos. Soon after, it flew to another tree where I got a glimpse before losing it again. A couple minutes later it briefly flew back to the cedar where I soon lost it. It had a red cap and throat. The belly was grayish and the back was mostly black with some white. It seemed to favor the Himalayan Cedar with all the benches around it. Soon after I lost the sapsucker, an immature male ANHU started drinking from the holes. There were possibly two but I never saw two at the same time so I'm keeping the count to one.

Continuing bird. Seen very briefly as it flew from the Himalayan Cedar to another tree. I caught a glimpse of the white rump and black back before I lost it. In the tree, I spied many sapsucker holes. After waiting for a few minutes, it flew back to the Himalayan Cedar where I took some photos. Soon after, it flew to another tree where I got a glimpse before losing it again. A couple minutes later it briefly flew back to the cedar where I soon lost it. It had a red cap and throat. The belly was grayish and the back was mostly black with some white. It seemed to favor the Himalayan Cedar with all the benches around it. Soon after I lost the sapsucker, an immature male ANHU started drinking from the holes. There were possibly two but I never saw two at the same time so I'm keeping the count to one.

Locality: Red-naped Sapsucker spot, SW Stellar Dr.
Observation Details: Continuing, thank you to all who posted about it! Lifer!!  Easily found in the group of trees others are reporting it in (where my marker is placed, too). Look in the deciduous trees near a dip in the trail, by a large circular concrete thing on the ground between the trail and the houses. It flies back and forth in that stand of trees, creating/feeding on/defending its sap wells.  One of the most beautiful and handsome birds I've ever seen... Brilliant red throat and forehead, stately black bib, crisp black and white stripes on face, soft red smudges on nape (my favorite part, it was beautiful to look at!), two rows of barring on the back.  It makes incredible square sap wells, unlike anything I've seen before (I'm used to the Red-breasted's perfect little circular holes). It's also extremely territorial towards all birds who approach its sap squares, actively chasing away many relentless hummingbirds and one opportunistic RCKI. However, it didn't even cast a glance at the many barking dogs or curious humans that passed by.   What an amazing bird... I couldn't get enough of its antics, and watching it as it made its squares. Sometimes it would carefully run the side of its beak up and down a branch, not as though wiping it, but as though it was sensing where to peck next, for it would then start working on a square in that spot.   Truly remarkable!!

Locality: Golden Gate Park--Arboretum (San Francisco Botanical Garden)
Observation Details: Adult male, photos, continuing in "Cryptocarya alba" here: https://sfbg.gardenexplorer.org/taxon-3276.aspx.  One of two Red-naped Sapsuckers seen in the garden this winter.  Possibly the same returning male initially found by Alan Hopkins 11/13/21.   They are a scarce visitor to the West Coast from the interior mountains and Great Basin.  The nape, throat and back pattern are typical of this species. Note the even rows of small holes drilled in this tree by this bird so the sap bleeds. This species was split from the similar Yellow-bellied Sapsucker of Eastern North America in 1983.

Cleanly delineated black, white and red head pattern, and lack of any red on breast rule out RBSA or hybrid. The amount of black on the border around red throat suggests male YBSA, but the red nape and white patch on chin imply female RNSA.  Interesting to note, however, that both BOTW and Sibley indicate that YBSA occasionally CAN have red on the nape! "Sometimes confused with Yellow-bellied Sapsucker because of individual variation in amount of red on nape in BOTH species." (BOTW; emphasis mine). "Nape usually white, occasionally red" (Description of adult male YBSA, Sibley 2nd Ed.). If I take this into consideration, and since I didn't get a good view of the back of the bird to get an idea of the amount of white, I suppose then that I'm calling this a RNSA (as opposed to a YBSA) based on the white chin patch and the statistical likelihood that a RNSA would have a red nape.

Observation Details: Continuing; after some delay in finding the right end of the Bob Jones trail, I found the two Peruvian pepper trees by the maintenance shed mentioned in earlier posts, but also found that there had been recent and fairly extensive "maintenance" on the tree closest to the road/trail, as evidenced by the fallen limbs draped on lower limbs and the neatly piled cuttings along the trail.  I didn't see or hear anything for a while, and a passing local birder lamented that the bird had not been seen since the tree maintenance a few days earlier, noting how the tree work had cut into the bird's favorite area.  After she left, I heard the bird call from the taller tree closer to the maintenance shed.  A few minutes later, it flew into the shorter, shorn tree.  My local birder came back and noted that it was still returning to the same favorite area despite the disruption.  She told me the bird had been returning regularly to this location since 2017.  Did not allow many open views for photos.

Adult male. Red nape. Red throat bleeding over past malar. No black malar. Two bold white stripes on back. We were looking at the MacGillvray's Warbler when the sapsucker popped into view just below the MAWA. Diana noticed the sapsucker first. WHen I saw it, I could only see the front of its face poking out from behind the base of a small elm tree. I could see a bright red throat, bleeding into the malar. There was no black border to the red throat, a classic textbook Red-naped Sapsucker. The bird was initially along the inner loop trail, just south of the tower. It then flew into the large live oak on the SE corner of the main sanctuary, and then flew back. We then got good photos and were also able to see the red nape. The bird for the next hour moved around throughout the sanctuary, stopping briefly in the hackberry above the front drip by the tower. Later on, we saw it fly east out of the sanctuary into the open area.  We found it again in Tootache trees on the east edge of the open area of the sanctuary before it continued flying east.

Observation Details: Continuing just west of the Fragrance Garden, well seen in the same tree as found by Alan Hopkins. Working its way up and down multiple limbs, sometimes licking the sap and then drilling some more, watched over briefly by an Anna's hummingbird. Did not hear any vocalization. Red nape separated from red crest by a black band, with black and white facial markings. Red neck bordered by thin smudgy black line, with no red on slightly yellowish dark speckled breast. Two broad light vertical rows of slightly greenish-yellow spots on the upper two-thirds of the back, coalescing to white spots/bands on the lower part, along with broad white bands on the sides of the folded wings. Photos obtained.

Media notes: bird #1
Observation Details: Two female types - although both had interesting plumages that appeared to be nicely intermediate between RNSA and YBSA, we received feedback that these bird's were within range of RNSA. Both foraging in madrones at pullout at (31.5192502, -109.0045918).  Comments on apparent hybrid plumage traits: Full black malar stripe (YBSA) and red patch on back of head (RNSA), and messy yellowish markings across mantle (not as restricted to two narrow rows as on pure RNSA). One had larger red nape than the other, and the mantle markings differed slightly; with one more broadly washed with yellow markings and one with more orderly (but messy) rows.

Private residence! please be respectful. Seen by myself and Sandy Kroeger my neighbor while photographing the RB Nuthatch. Strong and bold white wing-patch. Eliminated Yellow-bellied due to obvious red on top/black bottom color of nape. Also, eliminated YB Sap due to extensive red on throat and high upper breast. The red on the throat extended past the black malar region seen on a Yellow-bellied. Honestly I never saw or did either of the observers get picture of the back. So, I did not see the other distinguishing field mark of the two white vertical stripes which further eliminates YB Sap. Though, in flight did not give off a highly whiteish appearance from behind. Call was a more harsh sounding “waaaaah” type call. YB’s have more of a downslur at the end that isn’t so harsh. Called several times. Responded vigorously to recorded call call. My first impression of the bird was "look for the red nape" when I saw it. Luckily my neighbor and great photographer Sandy Kroeger was there to take the wonderful pictures. I have studied a lot in the last few hours after the sighting. But, I would love to hear other peoples opinions. especially, since I have never confirmed one before.

Locality: Red-naped Sapsucker spot, SW Stellar Dr.
Observation Details: Continuing, thank you to all who posted about it! Lifer!!  Easily found in the group of trees others are reporting it in (where my marker is placed, too). Look in the deciduous trees near a dip in the trail, by a large circular concrete thing on the ground between the trail and the houses. It flies back and forth in that stand of trees, creating/feeding on/defending its sap wells.  One of the most beautiful and handsome birds I've ever seen... Brilliant red throat and forehead, stately black bib, crisp black and white stripes on face, soft red smudges on nape (my favorite part, it was beautiful to look at!), two rows of barring on the back.  It makes incredible square sap wells, unlike anything I've seen before (I'm used to the Red-breasted's perfect little circular holes). It's also extremely territorial towards all birds who approach its sap squares, actively chasing away many relentless hummingbirds and one opportunistic RCKI. However, it didn't even cast a glance at the many barking dogs or curious humans that passed by.   What an amazing bird... I couldn't get enough of its antics, and watching it as it made its squares. Sometimes it would carefully run the side of its beak up and down a branch, not as though wiping it, but as though it was sensing where to peck next, for it would then start working on a square in that spot.   Truly remarkable!!
Pictures to be added.

Continuing bird found 2 days earlier by Darian Santner.  Darian was there again this morning, and he, Tait, Steve, and I finally got brief but great views at close range, after long bouts of crazy frenetic chasing between it and the territorial Red-breasteds. On a couple of occasions the birds whizzed right over our heads but disappeared out of view before we could see them well. Luckily for us, the Red-naped cooperated by flying to a perch directly in front of us, because after that view, all went quiet and there was no more sapsucker activity noticeable in the area. Locality: Fort Lowell Park and Pantano Wash
Media notes: Adult male. Elevation: 758 m. Date added to IBC: June 22, 2016.

Observation Details: Continuing bird found today by LC on the CBC. Located in the large willows on the back side of the park, moved around a decent bit. Appears to be an adult female, based on the slight white in the chin and the lack of red beneath the eye. Yellow-bellied eliminated by lack of a strong black border to the red throat and a visible red nape. Appears to have no signs of hybridization with red-breasted or yellow-bellied. 3rd attempt for this individual which has been here for three weeks. Immediately found pecking a eucalyptus after pulling up. Located at the grassy picnic area above the main parking lot. Two clear white stripes running through head bordered by thick black. Red nape.  **After long review of whether this is a YBSA, a RNSA, or a YBSA x RNSA hybrid, I am happy to call this a red-naped, simply because more features point towards that than a yellow-bellied.  A hybrid would be so hard to positively ID, so I am sticking with red-nape.

Continuing; after some delay in finding the right end of the Bob Jones trail, I found the two Peruvian pepper trees by the maintenance shed mentioned in earlier posts, but also found that there had been recent and fairly extensive "maintenance" on the tree closest to the road/trail, as evidenced by the fallen limbs draped on lower limbs and the neatly piled cuttings along the trail.  I didn't see or hear anything for a while, and a passing local birder lamented that the bird had not been seen since the tree maintenance a few days earlier, noting how the tree work had cut into the bird's favorite area.  After she left, I heard the bird call from the taller tree closer to the maintenance shed.  A few minutes later, it flew into the shorter, shorn tree.  My local birder came back and noted that it was still returning to the same favorite area despite the disruption.  She told me the bird had been returning regularly to this location since 2017.  Did not allow many open views for photos.

Observation Details: *Early. Initially flushed out from deep within a pine and then relocated nearby in a juniper. Flushed again and only glimpsed briefly in flight. At this point, I was thinking it was a good candidate for a YBSA given its affinity for junipers/pines and the slightly early date (in my experience, YBSA tend to be furtive and stick to Scotch pines (?) and other similar tree species)). Decided to drive through town looking for it and narrowed in on a nonnative pine on the side of the road that looked good for a sapsucker. Sure enough, there it was attending sap wells against the bark, but the red nape, back pattern, etc indicate RNSA. Not conventional breeding habitat for the species, and given the sap wells on the pine, I wonder if it overwintered.

Media notes: bird #1
Observation Details: Two female types - although both had interesting plumages that appeared to be nicely intermediate between RNSA and YBSA, we received feedback that these bird's were within range of RNSA. Both foraging in madrones at pullout at (31.5192502, -109.0045918).  Comments on apparent hybrid plumage traits: Full black malar stripe (YBSA) and red patch on back of head (RNSA), and messy yellowish markings across mantle (not as restricted to two narrow rows as on pure RNSA). One had larger red nape than the other, and the mantle markings differed slightly; with one more broadly washed with yellow markings and one with more orderly (but messy) rows.

Cleanly delineated black, white and red head pattern, and lack of any red on breast rule out RBSA or hybrid. The amount of black on the border around red throat suggests male YBSA, but the red nape and white patch on chin imply female RNSA.  Interesting to note, however, that both BOTW and Sibley indicate that YBSA occasionally CAN have red on the nape! "Sometimes confused with Yellow-bellied Sapsucker because of individual variation in amount of red on nape in BOTH species." (BOTW; emphasis mine). "Nape usually white, occasionally red" (Description of adult male YBSA, Sibley 2nd Ed.). If I take this into consideration, and since I didn't get a good view of the back of the bird to get an idea of the amount of white, I suppose then that I'm calling this a RNSA (as opposed to a YBSA) based on the white chin patch and the statistical likelihood that a RNSA would have a red nape.

Locality: Pescadero Creek Rd.-- Butano Creek riparian area
Observation Details: Continuing. Seen downstream from bridge at Pescadero Creek Road where the creek bends to the left.  There is an obvious tree near the North bank that has been snapped off along the trunk leaving about 2-3m section of open trunk pointing straight up. The bird was in the tall trees behind the broken tree. I watched it for maybe two minutes before it flew off downstream around the bend for me. It stayed on the North side of the creek. After about 10 minutes, it returned to the same tree with the many closely-spaced drill holes. I watched it for maybe 10 minutes more and took many photos. As I was heading back upstream, I heard pecking close by.  The bird was maybe 10m in front of me pecking away at the top of a dead broken snag.  I took a few more poor backlit photos.  The head pattern is very striking. Red crown, nape, throat, and a small spot below and behind the eye that was not visible in the field. The red on the crown and nape are separated by black. There is a white eyeline beginning behind the eye and running to the nape. There is a stronger white malar line.  The red throat is crisply bordered by black and then white.  There is no red in the breast.  Vertical white stripe on the flanks is bold and clear.  Two vertical white lines on black back are obvious and somewhat spotty.  Underside is white with smudgy fine chevrons of black.

Very likely a pure female Red-naped Sapsucker. This bird was first reported this morning by Roger Muskat. It is about a half-mile west of Pedrick Rd. on the south side of the creek and bridge. It favors a group of flowering fruit trees around (38.5262103, -121.8102338). I approached this spot and the sapsucker immediately flew out of the flowering trees along the edge of the field, flying towards the creek. It stopped briefly in a black walnut on the Solano side, where I was able to get one photo, before it flew across the creek into Yolo Co. from which I don’t think it returned (I never saw it again in the next hour of searching).   When I first saw this bird I instantly thought “OMG, this might be a pure bird!” (Having seen so many local sapsuckers go down the hybrid path). The back was black with two distinct white “red-naped rows”, more defined than I have seen before on any hybrid. The red nape was completely separated from the red crown, there was no bleeding whatsoever. The throat was red with a white chin (a feature shown almost solely in female RNSA), with no signs of red bleeding into the chest. The bird lacked a black breastband, which though strange could indicate that this bird is coming out of juvenile plumage, and at this date is admittedly something that could point to YBSA lineage. However looking online at many photos taken well with the normal range of RNSA, this seems to be a stage that RNSA females go through. I did not get a great view of facial pattern in person, but it seemed pretty good for pure RNSA, no signs of bleeding, limited black border on the throat, etc. My one photo seems to show the bird having a lot of white on the face, something that can be more characteristic of YBSA, but I honestly think my photo doesn’t show the exact ratio of white to black on the face (somewhat of a weird angle).   So in conclusion I think this very well could be a pure RNSA, and am at least temporarily posting it as such to get the word out. Hopefully others can follow up and get more photos and a conclusive identification can be reached. If this bird ends up being a hybrid RNSA x YBSA I will gladly change it to such, but I think it has a good shot at being a pure bird.

Locality: Folsom Lake SRA--Snipes-Pershing Ravine and Rollingwood Bluffs
Observation Details: Stunningly beautiful male found by Gavin Stacey 2/7.  Initially spotted in the oak at the NE corner of Tanglewood Cir. @ (38.6731218, -121.1924926), where it spent about 15 minutes resting and foraging by flaking off bark.  Solid red crown bordered in black, paler red patch on nape, entirely red throat bordered by black bib below.  Small patch of red behind eye, upper breast pale yellow.  Bold white line from top of bill wrapping around throat before fading into yellow breast.  Two distinct yet bold rows of white spots down back, more white than shown by Red-breasted and less than Yellow-bellied Sapsucker.  No blending of red between crown and nape, nor any hint of red on breast that would suggest a hybrid with RBSA.

Media notes: On Pittosporum undulatum

Observation Details: This sapsucker seems to have all the characteristics of a male 1st-year Red-naped:  1) black-&-white face with red crown, 2) white chin, red throat, and spotty black bib, 3) a very small faint patch of red in nape, 4) incomplete black border between red throat and whitish moustachial stripe, 5) two distinct rows of pale barring on back, 6) juvenile-like barring on breast (the last juvenile characteristic to completely molt away, according to Mlodinow, et al., in Birding Vol 38 (6), Page 48.  This article describes  "many first-cycle Red-napeds retaining a juvenal breast pattern well into winter.").  We see no vestige of any cross with red-breasted sapsucker, and none of the features mentioned above seem to require any element from yellow-bellied.

One female with lots of white on throat near post office; the bird was near 2 Red-breasted Sapsuckers, but I could not determine if any were paired with another. The second bird was the same female seen on 3 July on Willow Street. It was feeding young in a nest in a cottonwood with a Red-breasted Sapsucker. I determined that it was a female because it had a narrow row of white feathering at the base of the bill and slightly more white on the back than just two neat stripes, and the red on the nape were dull. I saw the Red-naped Sapsucker bring food to young in the nest five times during a 30-minute period before the Red-breasted fed them, and then the Red-breasted brought food twice in a 4-minute span. The nest was 20 feet up in a 35-foot tall cottonwood. The Red-breasted drummed once on a metal light.

Locality: Pescadero Marsh and Natural Preserve--end of Water Lane and vicinity
Red-naped Sapsucker spot, SW Stellar Dr.
Observation Details: Continuing, thank you to all who posted about it! Lifer!!  Easily found in the group of trees others are reporting it in (where my marker is placed, too). Look in the deciduous trees near a dip in the trail, by a large circular concrete thing on the ground between the trail and the houses. It flies back and forth in that stand of trees, creating/feeding on/defending its sap wells.  One of the most beautiful and handsome birds I've ever seen... Brilliant red throat and forehead, stately black bib, crisp black and white stripes on face, soft red smudges on nape (my favorite part, it was beautiful to look at!), two rows of barring on the back.  It makes incredible square sap wells, unlike anything I've seen before (I'm used to the Red-breasted's perfect little circular holes). It's also extremely territorial towards all birds who approach its sap squares, actively chasing away many relentless hummingbirds and one opportunistic RCKI. However, it didn't even cast a glance at the many barking dogs or curious humans that passed by.   What an amazing bird... I couldn't get enough of its antics, and watching it as it made its squares. Sometimes it would carefully run the side of its beak up and down a branch, not as though wiping it, but as though it was sensing where to peck next, for it would then start working on a square in that spot.   Truly remarkable!!

Depending on molt timing, these birds are at least immatures and possibly adults.  While until yesterday I had not seen a Red-naped Sapsucker at my home that wasn't molting in a chest band (yesterday I had a male with a sharply demarcated black chest band), today I had a male with a mostly--about 75%--black chest band.  I am sure I have seen a minimum of 50 Red-naped Sapsuckers in my yard this fall.

Locality: Los Angeles County Arboretum & Botanic Garden

Observation Details: I parked on the east side near the entrance and walked to the set of pepper trees near the covered picnic area at the southeast corner of the park (near the intersection of Winfield Blvd and Old Quarry Road) looking for the Red-naped Sapsucker, but didn't see him.  I then walked over the bridge to the west side of the lake and followed the trail up to the bridge.  I've never seen Coyote Creek so high!  I walked back to the pepper trees and found the Sapsucker in the fourth pepper tree from the southern end of the park at about 9:15AM.  It flew over to the Cork Oak tree and back.  I then walk south along Coyote Creek for 3/4 of a mile and back and refound the Sapsucker on the same pepper tree a little before 10:00.  This time it flew to the Cork Oak Tree, and then farther north (a bit) to another tall pepper tree near the northern edge of the clump of pepper trees.

Continuing; after some delay in finding the right end of the Bob Jones trail, I found the two Peruvian pepper trees by the maintenance shed mentioned in earlier posts, but also found that there had been recent and fairly extensive "maintenance" on the tree closest to the road/trail, as evidenced by the fallen limbs draped on lower limbs and the neatly piled cuttings along the trail.  I didn't see or hear anything for a while, and a passing local birder lamented that the bird had not been seen since the tree maintenance a few days earlier, noting how the tree work had cut into the bird's favorite area.  After she left, I heard the bird call from the taller tree closer to the maintenance shed.  A few minutes later, it flew into the shorter, shorn tree.  My local birder came back and noted that it was still returning to the same favorite area despite the disruption.  She told me the bird had been returning regularly to this location since 2017.  Did not allow many open views for photos.

Continuing rarity on heavily scarred sycamore across the Guadalupe Creek at the intersection of Sycamore Creek and Thyme Creek. Too many creeks! J. Perry spotted the bird within 4 minutes of our arrival as other birders had provided great descriptions/directions. The bird worked the scarred section of the sycamore tree before it eventually went around the back side of the tree and we left to go look for SUTA.  Bird had red on throat, crown, and nape. Partly red throat that had white at the base of the lower mandible (chin), evident in one poor photo and photos of others. White markings on back in two neat rows. White patch on wings. Distinguishing features which separate RNSA from YBSA or hybrids are red on throat with white on chin, neat rows of white on back, and red on nape. We didn't hear the bird call.

Large immature female sapsucker. First seen fly into tall pine in southwest area of park in tree behind workout bench area. I observed the bird on the upper trunk climb upward, foraging. The bird then flew across the cement creek to the north side of park, where I further observed, though it took a few minutes to find the bird here: (35.2678890, -120.6638185). The bird had a white chin and red throat with only a faint black border, as well as a faint, or mottled black upper chest, which is indicative of younger sapsuckers. Its crown was red, separated from its red nape by a black bar. Its cheek was part of a thick black bar that extended from the lower crown through the eye and then became a mottled black bar. It had a yellowy-brownish supercilium bar bordered both above and below by black, and below the eyeline bar had a thick yellowy-brownish-and white bar that curved inward toward the chest. The bottom black bar extending at a downward angle from the lower mandible was also black mottled. It had a large, thick white wingbar surrounded by black, though its primaries had black-and-white mottling. Its tail had a series of thick white bars. Its underside, which I saw briefly a few times, was yellowy-and-white along with black-mottling. The back was black-and-yellowy brown mottled. Photos

Continuing wintering sapsucker. White wing patch  , Red-crown, red throat not completely bordered by black . visible small red patch on lower back of head  . Black with two neat and organized white bars dorsally. (rather than disorganized buffy yellow bars of YBSA) Black crescent on chest. breast and flanks creamy yellow esp. in lower belly. All the key field marks confirm to me that this bird is a pure RNSA and not a hybrid or YBSA. photos show key features.  MOB.  Faithfully feeding in Liquid Amber near trail and footbridge south/ east corner of swimming lake.

Locality: Golden Gate Park--Arboretum (San Francisco Botanical Garden)
Observation Details: Found by Alan Hopkins yesterday. NP was on it in the previous reported location. Lines and colors in the head and face seem to match up well with RNSA. The age of the bird is in question - what seemed to be a brown wash resolved into more of a yellow in better light. On a softer note, the shelling or ticking on the sides of the breast is neatly developed and not muddy or incomplete. The white patch is well developed. And there is something going on in the coverts, there seems to be two different generations but woodpecker molt is all cattywampus. Peter showed up and we looked at it for a while, eliminated HY (though not 100%) and I didn't like adult and he suggested SY. If anyone managed to get photos of the primary coverts (tiny, dark feathers, just sticking out from the white patch, at the base of the primaries) please send these along, you can crop just to that area. Unfortunately they are often covered by the breast feathers. Short video of it preening: https://youtu.be/2pxrdQQftkg

Very likely a pure female Red-naped Sapsucker. This bird was first reported this morning by Roger Muskat. It is about a half-mile west of Pedrick Rd. on the south side of the creek and bridge. It favors a group of flowering fruit trees around (38.5262103, -121.8102338). I approached this spot and the sapsucker immediately flew out of the flowering trees along the edge of the field, flying towards the creek. It stopped briefly in a black walnut on the Solano side, where I was able to get one photo, before it flew across the creek into Yolo Co. from which I don’t think it returned (I never saw it again in the next hour of searching).   When I first saw this bird I instantly thought “OMG, this might be a pure bird!” (Having seen so many local sapsuckers go down the hybrid path). The back was black with two distinct white “red-naped rows”, more defined than I have seen before on any hybrid. The red nape was completely separated from the red crown, there was no bleeding whatsoever. The throat was red with a white chin (a feature shown almost solely in female RNSA), with no signs of red bleeding into the chest. The bird lacked a black breastband, which though strange could indicate that this bird is coming out of juvenile plumage, and at this date is admittedly something that could point to YBSA lineage. However looking online at many photos taken well with the normal range of RNSA, this seems to be a stage that RNSA females go through. I did not get a great view of facial pattern in person, but it seemed pretty good for pure RNSA, no signs of bleeding, limited black border on the throat, etc. My one photo seems to show the bird having a lot of white on the face, something that can be more characteristic of YBSA, but I honestly think my photo doesn’t show the exact ratio of white to black on the face (somewhat of a weird angle).   So in conclusion I think this very well could be a pure RNSA, and am at least temporarily posting it as such to get the word out. Hopefully others can follow up and get more photos and a conclusive identification can be reached. If this bird ends up being a hybrid RNSA x YBSA I will gladly change it to such, but I think it has a good shot at being a pure bird.

Locality: Folsom Lake SRA--Snipes-Pershing Ravine and Rollingwood Bluffs
Observation Details: Stunningly beautiful male found by Gavin Stacey 2/7.  Initially spotted in the oak at the NE corner of Tanglewood Cir. @ (38.6731218, -121.1924926), where it spent about 15 minutes resting and foraging by flaking off bark.  Solid red crown bordered in black, paler red patch on nape, entirely red throat bordered by black bib below.  Small patch of red behind eye, upper breast pale yellow.  Bold white line from top of bill wrapping around throat before fading into yellow breast.  Two distinct yet bold rows of white spots down back, more white than shown by Red-breasted and less than Yellow-bellied Sapsucker.  No blending of red between crown and nape, nor any hint of red on breast that would suggest a hybrid with RBSA.

Observation Details: This sapsucker seems to have all the characteristics of a male 1st-year Red-naped:  1) black-&-white face with red crown, 2) white chin, red throat, and spotty black bib, 3) a very small faint patch of red in nape, 4) incomplete black border between red throat and whitish moustachial stripe, 5) two distinct rows of pale barring on back, 6) juvenile-like barring on breast (the last juvenile characteristic to completely molt away, according to Mlodinow, et al., in Birding Vol 38 (6), Page 48.  This article describes  "many first-cycle Red-napeds retaining a juvenal breast pattern well into winter.").  We see no vestige of any cross with red-breasted sapsucker, and none of the features mentioned above seem to require any element from yellow-bellied.

Adult male with full black chest shield and red throat only partially framed in black. Presumed returning bird from last winter. Working sap wells in Liquidambar at north end of lawn opposite north entry to parking lot B. Tuft of red in black auricular on both sides of face thought to indicate interbreeding with RBSA lineage - this is a very common feature in RBSA I observe in SOCAL, Decision to assign to hybrid category is somewhat arbitrary. I currently assign individuals such in which there is a single and  very limited plumage anomaly to the species on the presumption that the underlying gene(s) are now widely incorporated into the species gene pool due to historical and/or continuing introgression with the sister species. i reserve the "hybrid" category for individuals that show multiple plumage anomalies, recognizing that they also may not be F1 hybrids.

Bird initially flew out of an elm in the cemetery to pines just out on City Park 9 golf course about midway along the cemetery south boundary.  These Austrian pines have been heavily used by sapsuckers, mostly Yellow-bellied Sapsuckers in winter, over the last few decades.  They were used this winter by an adult male YbSapsucker and the Red-naped Sapsuckers was reworking some of the best, most recent sap well patches.  It had a somewhat diffuse red patch on the nape, solid red crown, solid red throat, black border to the throat was incomplete and thin, back coloration was black and white (without the "brown sugar" coloration in the middle of the back shown by YbSapsuckers of all ages).  Big wide, white wing stripe along the side of the body.  Silent.  No doubt a migrant, timing is perfect, this site has a history of this species in spring and September-October.

Media notes: Photo by Dow Lambert.  Dow found the bird at the same location on 4/4/19 and took these excellent photos.
Observation Details: We had good looks as the bird worked cedar trees at the west end of RR Bridge trestle. It showed a striking red crown, red throat, and red nape mark, along with bold black and white pattern on its face.  It had a distinct red nape patch separated from the red of the crown by a black line that continued around the back of head. The red nape patch showed a little blurriness around its edges where it merged with the white supercilium.  The black eyeline on its face was outlined above and below by white.  Its chin and throat were entirely red, so possibly a male.  There was a black bib on its upper breast that extended below the red in its throat, with hint of yellow wash in the stripes below the black upper breast.  The lower part of body and wings appeared like a typical sapsucker.  There were Red-breasted Sapsuckers nearby for good comparison.

One female with lots of white on throat near post office; the bird was near 2 Red-breasted Sapsuckers, but I could not determine if any were paired with another. The second bird was the same female seen on 3 July on Willow Street. It was feeding young in a nest in a cottonwood with a Red-breasted Sapsucker. I determined that it was a female because it had a narrow row of white feathering at the base of the bill and slightly more white on the back than just two neat stripes, and the red on the nape were dull. I saw the Red-naped Sapsucker bring food to young in the nest five times during a 30-minute period before the Red-breasted fed them, and then the Red-breasted brought food twice in a 4-minute span. The nest was 20 feet up in a 35-foot tall cottonwood. The Red-breasted drummed once on a metal light.

This small to medium-sized woodpecker had a straight bill that would have extended backward approximately to the rear edge of the auriculars, a relatively steep forehead and a gently rounded to somewhat flattened crown.  I thought the head was unremarkable in size and that the neck was short and stocky, so this bird did not have a blocky appearance to the head that is typical of the local woodpeckers.  The body was plump and full chested, and the tail was about as long as the body without the head.  I further thought the primary projection was roughly comparable to the full length of the exposed secondaries, and that the wingtips reached at least halfway out the tail.  The legs were short and stout.  This was a boldly patterned and relatively brightly colored bird.  The forehead and crown were a bright crimson-red back to the nape.  Framing the red cap was a black line that extended along the edge of the crown from the base of the bill and over the supercilium before connecting across the junction of the crown and nape.  The nape was obviously washed with red, but I thought back of the neck was blackish and mottled.  The black that bordered the crown also extended down in front of the eye.  The white supercilium therefore began right above the eye, from which it extended back over the auriculars to their rear terminus at the red nape.  The solidly black mask was conspicuous and well-defined as it extended back across the auriculars to their rear terminus where it narrowed, but I think the black continued down the side of the neck.  Demarcating the lower edge of the mask was a white moustachial-stripe that extended diagonally across the face from the base of the upper mandible, under the eye and around the throat.  The throat was the same shade of crimson-red as the cap, and this color extended across the malar region to meet the white moustachial-stripe.  I therefore noted black in the malar region only as a narrow wedge that extended a short way back from the base of the bill.  The red also extended across the chin and out to the corners of the throat.  Demarcating the lower edge of the throat was a breast-band that was roughly crescent-shaped and mottled with deep buff on a black background.  I think the white of the submoustachial stripe continued around the corners of the breast-band, but I can really only be sure that some paler color demarcated this band.  The sides and flanks were pale gray with blurry, blackish streaks at the sides and on the foreflanks, but the markings on the lower flanks were more wedges if not V-shaped chevrons.  I am not now sure about the color of the belly below the breast-band, but I did not think it was bright yellow, and I am certain that the undertail coverts were white with black streaks along the outer edges.  The back and scapulars were mostly black but with diffuse braces of white with blackish mottling on either side near the demarcation between the back and scapulars.  The inner part of each wing was solidly black but there was a broad blaze or wide crescent of white along the leading edge of the each wing that presumably covered the outer few coverts.  The remiges were black with white barring, but I am less sure about the pattern on the inner secondaries.  My views of the tail were less than ideal, but from the side it appeared to be mostly if not entirely black.  I think the rump was white (at least along the edges) but it also seemed to have a few, blackish streaks.  I noted that the bill and eyes were both dark, but I failed to note their color more precisely.  I did notice that the legs and feet were a dingy gray color.

Locality: Red-naped Sapsucker spot, SW Stellar Dr.
Observation Details: Continuing, thank you to all who posted about it! Lifer!!  Easily found in the group of trees others are reporting it in (where my marker is placed, too). Look in the deciduous trees near a dip in the trail, by a large circular concrete thing on the ground between the trail and the houses. It flies back and forth in that stand of trees, creating/feeding on/defending its sap wells.  One of the most beautiful and handsome birds I've ever seen... Brilliant red throat and forehead, stately black bib, crisp black and white stripes on face, soft red smudges on nape (my favorite part, it was beautiful to look at!), two rows of barring on the back.  It makes incredible square sap wells, unlike anything I've seen before (I'm used to the Red-breasted's perfect little circular holes). It's also extremely territorial towards all birds who approach its sap squares, actively chasing away many relentless hummingbirds and one opportunistic RCKI. However, it didn't even cast a glance at the many barking dogs or curious humans that passed by.   What an amazing bird... I couldn't get enough of its antics, and watching it as it made its squares. Sometimes it would carefully run the side of its beak up and down a branch, not as though wiping it, but as though it was sensing where to peck next, for it would then start working on a square in that spot.   Truly remarkable!!

Locality: Mile Square Regional Park, Fountain Valley

Observation Details: Red nape. From some angles, red throat looked fully bordered by black, like Yellow-bellied Sapsucker.   Photos show some white feathers on chin (like female red-naped) and some red invading black malar stripe (like male red-naped), so sex uncertain.    Further comment from Darren:  "I find the photos of the red-naped/yellow-bellied to look a lot like the illustration of red-naped female in Sibley:  nearly complete black border to throat with a few invading red feathers at the corner, subdued red nape compared to red crown, a little bit of a white chin.  And the back pattern looks more like red-naped, with a dark vertical patch in the middle of the upper back, and more diagonal white markings rather than barring."

A red-naped sapsucker continued at McKinney Falls State Park on 3-1-16 . The bird was present in the only cottonwood tree on the trail between Smith Visitor Center and the stone ruins of the old horse trainer's barn. It had been observed in the cottonwood on the two previous days. The cottonwood is directly across the trail from some fenced-in electrical equipment and a large clump of prickly pear cactus, just before you reach the ruins. The stone ruins are visible on the right side of the road just before you arrive at the parking lot adjacent to Smith Visitor Center. Thanks to Arman Moreno and Eric Carpenter, whose eBird reports and directions made it possible for me to see the bird.    Adult male yellow-bellied sapsuckers can rarely show some red on the nape. However, in the red-naped sapsucker, the red throat invades or completely covers the black border along the malar, and the pale markings on the back are whiter and more restricted. Female red-naped sapsuckers with maximal red on the chin and throat closely resemble the male yellow-bellied, but usually have white on the uppermost chin and a hint of red on the nape, as the bird that I photographed does; The bird that I photographed is an adult female red-naped sapsucker, distinguished most easily from the adult male red-naped sapsucker by the limited amount of red on her throat. Adult female yellow-bellied sapsuckers do not have red coloration on the throat. Another difference in the two species is that the spotting on the back of the red-naped sapsucker is more clearly organized into two rows, as it is in the bird that I observed and photographed.

An apparent adult female, back for at least its 3rd consecutive winter here. As usual, in its same spot in same tree, a Peruvian (Calif.) Pepper tree, along immediate east side of the Santiago Street pedestrian bridge, on the north bank of Santiago Creek. The bird known to be present this season since at least 29 November, 2011. Got excellent views this time, with the bird at eye level and fairly close. Got nice pics this time. Bold black and white in face, with no red at all seen in the auricular area (black or white areas).  Red nape. Presumably same bird, as each year this bird seems to show both female and male features.  Red throat completely framed in black, except for a small area at lower corners, where red washes out ("interrupts") the black frame. The red of throat also shows a narrow sliver of white feathering at base of lower mandible. The red interrupting the black frame is supposedly a feature of male RNSA, although the white chin area is more typical of a female (which should otherwise show a complete black frame to throat). Interestingly, at rest, or in "concealment mode", with its neck scrunched in, I could not see much--or almost any--black at base of throat, the black being just along the side of the throat to where the red washes it out at the lower corner. Then when it seemed to be at alert, like ready to flee, it stretched out its neck, which resulted in (or revealed) a broad black lower border to red throat patch, the black being quite prominent, like a bib.

Observation Details: Found by Blythe Wilde on November 10, 2017 on the Cuesta College campus, between the Cuesta College Library and building 2100, at the base of a low-lying pepper tree. Today the bird was working the trunk of the same tree. It also flew over to an adjacent pepper tree and ate the fruit there, before returning to the first tree to continue drilling holes. Black upper parts, with rows of white barring running down each side of the back; red crown with a black border; red patch on the nape; black eye line bordered by bold white lines; slight peak at the back of the head; males have red chin and throat, lacking the complete black border seen on Yellow-bellied Sapsucker; black bib covering the upper breast; whitish lower breast and belly with a yellow wash; dusky streaks along the sides and flanks. This male Red-naped Sapsucker was feeding at holes it had excavated in a Eucalyptus tree at the upper end of the Egret Campground at Lake Casitas.  I concluded it was a sapsucker based on the amount of white in the wings and the way it was working a line of holes in the tree.  It had a distinct face pattern so it was not a Red-breasted (also seen in nearby trees).  It had an all red throat.  At first, the red seemed almost outlined in black but closer examination showed the black outline was not complete.  It had an obvious red nape.  It had two white stripes down the back separated by a black area.  Based on all these patterns, I concluded it was a Red-naped Sapsucker.

Adult male. Red nape. Red throat bleeding over past malar. No black malar. Two bold white stripes on back. We were looking at the MacGillvray's Warbler when the sapsucker popped into view just below the MAWA. Diana noticed the sapsucker first. WHen I saw it, I could only see the front of its face poking out from behind the base of a small elm tree. I could see a bright red throat, bleeding into the malar. There was no black border to the red throat, a classic textbook Red-naped Sapsucker. The bird was initially along the inner loop trail, just south of the tower. It then flew into the large live oak on the SE corner of the main sanctuary, and then flew back. We then got good photos and were also able to see the red nape. The bird for the next hour moved around throughout the sanctuary, stopping briefly in the hackberry above the front drip by the tower. Later on, we saw it fly east out of the sanctuary into the open area.  We found it again in Tootache trees on the east edge of the open area of the sanctuary before it continued flying east.

Adult male seen very well, uncommonly cooperative.  In small (remaining) tree stand to road junction at top of ridge.  Seemed to favor two decaying western hemlock trees and a couple of nearby red alders.  Observed for ~30 min.    I observed a sapsucker fly across the road that immediately caught my attention as it had a lot of white in the back and looked very different than the expected Red Breasted.  It took a while to track it down, but once I located the trees it was favoring I was able to get great views.  Often perched for long periods in excellent light.  Several times it flew low overhead between trees on each side of road.  Initially I thought this might be a Yellow-bellied or a hybrid based on the amount of white on the back.  With good views I was able to see the following:  Black and white face pattern typical of species including extensive bight red throat with red along side obscuring any black border along the sides but clearly boarded black below between throat and belly; bright red nape patch and extensive red crown.  Back had two rather broad white panels with fine black barring separated by black in mid back. large pure white wing panels and much white in tertials, much white in rump and middle tail.  Pale below with black border below red throat, yellowish wash to breast/belly, flanks grayish with fine black barring. Obtained are few very poor digiscope photos through binos.

This sapsucker seems to have all the characteristics of a male 1st-year Red-naped:  1) black-&-white face with red crown, 2) white chin, red throat, and spotty black bib, 3) a very small faint patch of red in nape, 4) incomplete black border between red throat and whitish moustachial stripe, 5) two distinct rows of pale barring on back, 6) juvenile-like barring on breast (the last juvenile characteristic to completely molt away, according to Mlodinow, et al., in Birding Vol 38 (6), Page 48.  This article describes  "many first-cycle Red-napeds retaining a juvenal breast pattern well into winter.").  We see no vestige of any cross with red-breasted sapsucker, and none of the features mentioned above seem to require any element from yellow-bellied.

Bird initially flew out of an elm in the cemetery to pines just out on City Park 9 golf course about midway along the cemetery south boundary.  These Austrian pines have been heavily used by sapsuckers, mostly Yellow-bellied Sapsuckers in winter, over the last few decades.  They were used this winter by an adult male YbSapsucker and the Red-naped Sapsuckers was reworking some of the best, most recent sap well patches.  It had a somewhat diffuse red patch on the nape, solid red crown, solid red throat, black border to the throat was incomplete and thin, back coloration was black and white (without the "brown sugar" coloration in the middle of the back shown by YbSapsuckers of all ages).  Big wide, white wing stripe along the side of the body.  Silent.  No doubt a migrant, timing is perfect, this site has a history of this species in spring and September-October.

I have been birding worldwide since 1976. At my townhouse gardens, the usual sapsucker sp (ruber) is seen from time to time in the much-used sapsucker tree which is within 20 meters of my kitchen and deck. This individual caught my eye -- it was a bit fluffed up despite the warm weather. May have been weak or sick. But was pecking away and moving around the trunk. Could this be a hybrid? I took more photos than those submitted. Dont' know if camera info is needed. Sorry to be late in reporting but since sighting, I have been traveling and as well, didn't know how easy it would be to crop and submit the photos. This is my first attempt at posting photos on eBird. I noticed this sp. was reported as rarity in Stanley Park, Vancouver.

Continuing bird finally re-found by Jim Lomax after a prolonged hunt for the bird from the parking lot north to the parking lot on the hill to the south and all points in between by the birders mentioned.   This quiet bird looks to be a male. Drilling holes and fairly active in the deciduous tree between the redwoods near the bathroom that is closed, on the southern end of the swimming lagoon. There is a sign right under it that says  "No lifeguard on duty." There was also fresh sapsucker holes drilled in the Liquid Ambar tree just to the east of this location.   Mario Balitbit, Richard Stratford, Dean Williams, Jim Lomax, Andrew Larson and Rebecca Olsen saw the bird with me... Thank you Jim!  Many folks took photos of the bird and I will post my photos asap.

Large immature female sapsucker. First seen fly into tall pine in southwest area of park in tree behind workout bench area. I observed the bird on the upper trunk climb upward, foraging. The bird then flew across the cement creek to the north side of park, where I further observed, though it took a few minutes to find the bird here: (35.2678890, -120.6638185). The bird had a white chin and red throat with only a faint black border, as well as a faint, or mottled black upper chest, which is indicative of younger sapsuckers. Its crown was red, separated from its red nape by a black bar. Its cheek was part of a thick black bar that extended from the lower crown through the eye and then became a mottled black bar. It had a yellowy-brownish supercilium bar bordered both above and below by black, and below the eyeline bar had a thick yellowy-brownish-and white bar that curved inward toward the chest. The bottom black bar extending at a downward angle from the lower mandible was also black mottled. It had a large, thick white wingbar surrounded by black, though its primaries had black-and-white mottling. Its tail had a series of thick white bars. Its underside, which I saw briefly a few times, was yellowy-and-white along with black-mottling. The back was black-and-yellowy brown mottled. Photos

Locality: Castle Wildland PP--South Fork Lakes Trail

Observation Details: Continuing; after some delay in finding the right end of the Bob Jones trail, I found the two Peruvian pepper trees by the maintenance shed mentioned in earlier posts, but also found that there had been recent and fairly extensive "maintenance" on the tree closest to the road/trail, as evidenced by the fallen limbs draped on lower limbs and the neatly piled cuttings along the trail.  I didn't see or hear anything for a while, and a passing local birder lamented that the bird had not been seen since the tree maintenance a few days earlier, noting how the tree work had cut into the bird's favorite area.  After she left, I heard the bird call from the taller tree closer to the maintenance shed.  A few minutes later, it flew into the shorter, shorn tree.  My local birder came back and noted that it was still returning to the same favorite area despite the disruption.  She told me the bird had been returning regularly to this location since 2017.  Did not allow many open views for photos.

Continuing bird. Seen very briefly as it flew from the Himalayan Cedar to another tree. I caught a glimpse of the white rump and black back before I lost it. In the tree, I spied many sapsucker holes. After waiting for a few minutes, it flew back to the Himalayan Cedar where I took some photos. Soon after, it flew to another tree where I got a glimpse before losing it again. A couple minutes later it briefly flew back to the cedar where I soon lost it. It had a red cap and throat. The belly was grayish and the back was mostly black with some white. It seemed to favor the Himalayan Cedar with all the benches around it. Soon after I lost the sapsucker, an immature male ANHU started drinking from the holes. There were possibly two but I never saw two at the same time so I'm keeping the count to one.

3rd attempt for this individual which has been here for three weeks. Immediately found pecking a eucalyptus after pulling up. Located at the grassy picnic area above the main parking lot. Two clear white stripes running through head bordered by thick black. Red nape.  **After long review of whether this is a YBSA, a RNSA, or a YBSA x RNSA hybrid, I am happy to call this a red-naped, simply because more features point towards that than a yellow-bellied.  A hybrid would be so hard to positively ID, so I am sticking with red-nape.

Adult male. Red nape. Red throat bleeding over past malar. No black malar. Two bold white stripes on back. We were looking at the MacGillvray's Warbler when the sapsucker popped into view just below the MAWA. Diana noticed the sapsucker first. WHen I saw it, I could only see the front of its face poking out from behind the base of a small elm tree. I could see a bright red throat, bleeding into the malar. There was no black border to the red throat, a classic textbook Red-naped Sapsucker. The bird was initially along the inner loop trail, just south of the tower. It then flew into the large live oak on the SE corner of the main sanctuary, and then flew back. We then got good photos and were also able to see the red nape. The bird for the next hour moved around throughout the sanctuary, stopping briefly in the hackberry above the front drip by the tower. Later on, we saw it fly east out of the sanctuary into the open area.  We found it again in Tootache trees on the east edge of the open area of the sanctuary before it continued flying east.

Male and female flew into yard, proceeded to call at eachother from separate locations then landed on the maple tree and made squeaky sounds at eachother. Male hopped onto female and copulated with some wing flapping. Once done he hopped off, they squeaked at eachother more, then after a few second hopped towards opposite sides of branch then flew away. Both had similar base marking (red patches on head, nape, chin and woodpecker coloration) but male had larger more vibrant red patches as well as a large black chest patch beneath red throat and more defined borders plumage coloration while female appeared more "messy". Came back about 8-10 minutes later.

Reported by Darian Santner to the Oregon Birding Discord, Portland area chat, and with an excellent photo of a clean RNSA individual. I arrived with Darian still on the scene as the RNSA squabbled with 2 RBSA on the cottonwoods. After about 5-10 minutes of this they split up and did not see them again before I left. Darian mentioned that the birds would squabble, break up, and begin squabbling again on the same tree as the pin below.  The individual was a male with a red throat with a cleanly demarcated black band below it. Only one red spot behind the eye on the black behind the eyes, clean red forecrown (clean black on hindcrown), red on nape, white line behind the eye. Clean white line from above the bill with a tinge of red bleeding into it behind the eye, wrapping around the red throat and black breast band. Tinge of yellow below the black breast band in the white on the underside near shoulder spur. The red behind the eye and a little in the white below the eye seems to be within range for pure per Macaulay and Sibley. For RBSA hybrid would expect to see red bleeding into the black breast band and in the black on the face and head, but everything seems to be cleanly demarcated. Ruling out YBSA hybrid with the cleaner looking barring on the back, the incomplete black border around the red throat and overall cleaner look.  Last seen here: 45.481723,-122.651812

Female sapsucker.  The chin and upper part of the throat was white with a band on red on the lower throat. There was a very small, but easily observable, red spot on the nape. The back is largely black with two fairly distinct lines of mottled feathers rather than the more widespread mottling as is seen in Yellow-bellied Sapsucker. The belly is very light yellow as is typical of many female Red-naped Sapsuckers.
Black bib, red under chin, white curving below chin around toward and then above bill, black through eye, white supercillium, red on crown. Photos coming.

Media notes: Bird #1
Observation Details: Apparently within range of variation for f rnsa.   Initially thought to be hybrids due to: Nicely intermediate with full black malar stripe (YBSA) and red patch on back of head (RNSA), and messy yellowish markings across mantle (not on restricted to two narrow rows as on pure RNSA). One had larger red nape than the other, and the mantle markings differed slightly; with one more broadly washed with yellow markings and one with more orderly (but messy) rows. Both in madrones at pullout at (31.5192502, -109.0045918).

Locality: Golden Gate Park--Arboretum (San Francisco Botanical Garden)
Observation Details: Found by Alan Hopkins yesterday. NP was on it in the previous reported location. Lines and colors in the head and face seem to match up well with RNSA. The age of the bird is in question - what seemed to be a brown wash resolved into more of a yellow in better light. On a softer note, the shelling or ticking on the sides of the breast is neatly developed and not muddy or incomplete. The white patch is well developed. And there is something going on in the coverts, there seems to be two different generations but woodpecker molt is all cattywampus. Peter showed up and we looked at it for a while, eliminated HY (though not 100%) and I didn't like adult and he suggested SY. If anyone managed to get photos of the primary coverts (tiny, dark feathers, just sticking out from the white patch, at the base of the primaries) please send these along, you can crop just to that area. Unfortunately they are often covered by the breast feathers. Short video of it preening: https://youtu.be/2pxrdQQftkg

First reported as a hybrid RNSA x YBSA but review of photos seems to suggest a RNSA. Red cap and throat and large wing patch indicate a sapsucker. The bird had a small but visible red patch on the nape, two rows of white lines on the back rather than the more extensive white on the YBSA, large red throat patch with large black border broken toward the bill. There was a very faint yellow wash on the breast and belly. I don’t know if any of these features suggest a hybrid. Observed at the top of the hill in the Garry oaks near the water reservoir.

Locality: Golden Gate Park--Arboretum (San Francisco Botanical Garden)
Observation Details: Continuing just west of the Fragrance Garden, well seen in the same tree as found by Alan Hopkins. Working its way up and down multiple limbs, sometimes licking the sap and then drilling some more, watched over briefly by an Anna's hummingbird. Did not hear any vocalization. Red nape separated from red crest by a black band, with black and white facial markings. Red neck bordered by thin smudgy black line, with no red on slightly yellowish dark speckled breast. Two broad light vertical rows of slightly greenish-yellow spots on the upper two-thirds of the back, coalescing to white spots/bands on the lower part, along with broad white bands on the sides of the folded wings. Photos obtained.

Locality: Scott Rd. property, Stevens County, NE WA
Observation Details: Frequent calls from Douglas fir yard tree; clinging to trunk ascending, took flight with chattering  vocalizations. Longitudinal white wing stripes, red crown and red nape patch, white back markings in a longitudinal row apparently separated from a second distinct row (but not clearly viewable from the photographed angle). Large dark auricular patch, thin white line behind eye. All red throat - likely an adult male - with red throat feathers extending into the black malar stripe near the base of the beak and breaking up the black 'frame'; however, this diagnostic field mark is somewhat problematic in the photos of the head tilted upward due to the black frame appearing more prominent - a characteristic of Yellow-bellied sapsucker - but the enlarged photo does reveal red colored pixels extending into the black frame. Locality: Pescadero Creek Rd.-- Butano Creek riparian area
Observation Details: Continuing. Seen downstream from bridge at Pescadero Creek Road where the creek bends to the left.  There is an obvious tree near the North bank that has been snapped off along the trunk leaving about 2-3m section of open trunk pointing straight up. The bird was in the tall trees behind the broken tree. I watched it for maybe two minutes before it flew off downstream around the bend for me. It stayed on the North side of the creek. After about 10 minutes, it returned to the same tree with the many closely-spaced drill holes. I watched it for maybe 10 minutes more and took many photos. As I was heading back upstream, I heard pecking close by.  The bird was maybe 10m in front of me pecking away at the top of a dead broken snag.  I took a few more poor backlit photos.  The head pattern is very striking. Red crown, nape, throat, and a small spot below and behind the eye that was not visible in the field. The red on the crown and nape are separated by black. There is a white eyeline beginning behind the eye and running to the nape. There is a stronger white malar line.  The red throat is crisply bordered by black and then white.  There is no red in the breast.  Vertical white stripe on the flanks is bold and clear.  Two vertical white lines on black back are obvious and somewhat spotty.  Underside is white with smudgy fine chevrons of black.

Locality: Folsom Lake SRA--Snipes-Pershing Ravine and Rollingwood Bluffs
Observation Details: Stunningly beautiful male found by Gavin Stacey 2/7.  Initially spotted in the oak at the NE corner of Tanglewood Cir. @ (38.6731218, -121.1924926), where it spent about 15 minutes resting and foraging by flaking off bark.  Solid red crown bordered in black, paler red patch on nape, entirely red throat bordered by black bib below.  Small patch of red behind eye, upper breast pale yellow.  Bold white line from top of bill wrapping around throat before fading into yellow breast.  Two distinct yet bold rows of white spots down back, more white than shown by Red-breasted and less than Yellow-bellied Sapsucker.  No blending of red between crown and nape, nor any hint of red on breast that would suggest a hybrid with RBSA.

Adult male with full black chest shield and red throat only partially framed in black. Presumed returning bird from last winter. Working sap wells in Liquidambar at north end of lawn opposite north entry to parking lot B. Tuft of red in black auricular on both sides of face thought to indicate interbreeding with RBSA lineage - this is a very common feature in RBSA I observe in SOCAL, Decision to assign to hybrid category is somewhat arbitrary. I currently assign individuals such in which there is a single and  very limited plumage anomaly to the species on the presumption that the underlying gene(s) are now widely incorporated into the species gene pool due to historical and/or continuing introgression with the sister species. i reserve the "hybrid" category for individuals that show multiple plumage anomalies, recognizing that they also may not be F1 hybrids.

Private residence! please be respectful. Seen by myself and Sandy Kroeger my neighbor while photographing the RB Nuthatch. Strong and bold white wing-patch. Eliminated Yellow-bellied due to obvious red on top/black bottom color of nape. Also, eliminated YB Sap due to extensive red on throat and high upper breast. The red on the throat extended past the black malar region seen on a Yellow-bellied. Honestly I never saw or did either of the observers get picture of the back. So, I did not see the other distinguishing field mark of the two white vertical stripes which further eliminates YB Sap. Though, in flight did not give off a highly whiteish appearance from behind. Call was a more harsh sounding “waaaaah” type call. YB’s have more of a downslur at the end that isn’t so harsh. Called several times. Responded vigorously to recorded call call. My first impression of the bird was "look for the red nape" when I saw it. Luckily my neighbor and great photographer Sandy Kroeger was there to take the wonderful pictures. I have studied a lot in the last few hours after the sighting. But, I would love to hear other peoples opinions. especially, since I have never confirmed one before.

Pescadero Creek Rd.-- Butano Creek riparian area
Observation Details: Sapsucker with red nape and clean white markings down back. Clean white line on face. Found across from ag field along the recently cleared / dredged Butano Creek riparian (access is near where Bean Hollow Road terminates at Pescadero Creek Road).  There is a crude "path" leftover by workers/machinery that runs downstream on the east bank from Pescadero Creek Road, we found the bird approximately 70 yards down in an alder on the same side as the "path", the holes it has been drilling are quite apparent in the tree making for a good field mark (and by the extensive nature of the holes it has probably been working that tree for a while now!). One note of caution: this isn't a maintained path, and it can be rough going (logs, mud, etc.) especially as you get further along down near where this bird was.

Locality: Red-naped Sapsucker spot, SW Stellar Dr.
Observation Details: Continuing, thank you to all who posted about it! Lifer!!  Easily found in the group of trees others are reporting it in (where my marker is placed, too). Look in the deciduous trees near a dip in the trail, by a large circular concrete thing on the ground between the trail and the houses. It flies back and forth in that stand of trees, creating/feeding on/defending its sap wells.  One of the most beautiful and handsome birds I've ever seen... Brilliant red throat and forehead, stately black bib, crisp black and white stripes on face, soft red smudges on nape (my favorite part, it was beautiful to look at!), two rows of barring on the back.  It makes incredible square sap wells, unlike anything I've seen before (I'm used to the Red-breasted's perfect little circular holes). It's also extremely territorial towards all birds who approach its sap squares, actively chasing away many relentless hummingbirds and one opportunistic RCKI. However, it didn't even cast a glance at the many barking dogs or curious humans that passed by.   What an amazing bird... I couldn't get enough of its antics, and watching it as it made its squares. Sometimes it would carefully run the side of its beak up and down a branch, not as though wiping it, but as though it was sensing where to peck next, for it would then start working on a square in that spot.   Truly remarkable!!

A red-naped sapsucker continued at McKinney Falls State Park on 3-1-16 . The bird was present in the only cottonwood tree on the trail between Smith Visitor Center and the stone ruins of the old horse trainer's barn. It had been observed in the cottonwood on the two previous days. The cottonwood is directly across the trail from some fenced-in electrical equipment and a large clump of prickly pear cactus, just before you reach the ruins. The stone ruins are visible on the right side of the road just before you arrive at the parking lot adjacent to Smith Visitor Center. Thanks to Arman Moreno and Eric Carpenter, whose eBird reports and directions made it possible for me to see the bird.    Adult male yellow-bellied sapsuckers can rarely show some red on the nape. However, in the red-naped sapsucker, the red throat invades or completely covers the black border along the malar, and the pale markings on the back are whiter and more restricted. Female red-naped sapsuckers with maximal red on the chin and throat closely resemble the male yellow-bellied, but usually have white on the uppermost chin and a hint of red on the nape, as the bird that I photographed does; The bird that I photographed is an adult female red-naped sapsucker, distinguished most easily from the adult male red-naped sapsucker by the limited amount of red on her throat. Adult female yellow-bellied sapsuckers do not have red coloration on the throat. Another difference in the two species is that the spotting on the back of the red-naped sapsucker is more clearly organized into two rows, as it is in the bird that I observed and photographed.

Or Yellow-bellied Red-naped hybrid.  New location on the wooded trail, past the boardwalk which heads northeast from the monument, beyond the gazebos, near the little group of little benches in the woods. I think this is a different bird than the male previously reported at the Mexican Breastworks 15 (which I also saw several weeks ago). This woodpecker is clearly showing a red nape, but not an extensive one.  According to Sibley's second edition, Yellow-bellied Sapsuckers can also sometimes have a red nape, but that the red throat with white chin is a field mark indicating Red-naped female. This chin/throat combination shows up well in the bottom photo.  Lacks black frame around the red and white throat, also more compatible with Red-naped female. I put the photos in the flicker bird id help group and the feedback is for Red Naped. In summary, the combination of an obvious but small red nape and a white chin with red throat suggest Red-naped female, according to Sibley's 2nd edition page 313, The chin and throat features are inconsistent with Yellow-bellied.     Later note...Someone left me a Flickr note suggesting that the back is too messy for a pure Red-Naped and that it might be a hybrid.  Am reconsidering the call and may revise.

Update: After asking a bunch of people for advice, the consensus seems to be that this is not too far from a pure red-naped sapsucker. The back pattern and the large amount of black in the face are within the range of a red-naped sapsucker. The only question is whether adult males can lack red on the nape (Sibley mentions the possibility for females). So I'm changing the ID from the original ID of yellow-bellied sapsucker to a red-naped sapsucker, while noting that it is possible there is some yellow-bellied ancestry involved.  Original description: Adult male. Absolutely no red on nape seen in the field, verified in photos. No red on face, red on crown and a reasonably large amount of red bordered by black on throat. Lemon yellow belly, messy black and white pattern on back. Silent. Not easy to separate from red-naped, but I'm leaning strongly towards yellow-bellied rather than red-naped. Multiple photos. Comments welcome!  I saw the bird on a sycamore along the fence of the RV park (Bonita Ranch RV campground), where an unofficial trail along the south fork to Bonita falls begins. The bird flew into the park after good views for several minutes. If anyone is interested in chasing this bird, this spot can be accessed by hiking along the creek (Bonita falls trail) from outside the RV park. The RV park itself is private property and may require an entrance fee.

Observation Details: Slender, mid-sized woodpecker with slim bill and distinctly separate red patches at chin, crown, and nape divided by white and black stripes. Chin patch with incomplete black border broken at curve. Two lines of white barring down solidly black back were well organized and relatively narrow in contrast to messier barring and usually browner background coloration on a YBSA. No obvious signs of hybridization.
