Media notes: Red chin and throat (male); red crown with a black border; red patch on the nape.
Observation Details: Found by Blythe Wilde on November 10, 2017 on the Cuesta College campus, between the Cuesta College Library and building 2100, at the base of a low-lying pepper tree. Today the bird was working the trunk of the same tree. It also flew over to an adjacent pepper tree and ate the fruit there, before returning to the first tree to continue drilling holes. Black upper parts, with rows of white barring running down each side of the back; red crown with a black border; red patch on the nape; black eye line bordered by bold white lines; slight peak at the back of the head; males have red chin and throat, lacking the complete black border seen on Yellow-bellied Sapsucker; black bib covering the upper breast; whitish lower breast and belly with a yellow wash; dusky streaks along the sides and flanks. This male Red-naped Sapsucker was feeding at holes it had excavated in a Eucalyptus tree at the upper end of the Egret Campground at Lake Casitas.  I concluded it was a sapsucker based on the amount of white in the wings and the way it was working a line of holes in the tree.  It had a distinct face pattern so it was not a Red-breasted (also seen in nearby trees).  It had an all red throat.  At first, the red seemed almost outlined in black but closer examination showed the black outline was not complete.  It had an obvious red nape.  It had two white stripes down the back separated by a black area.  Based on all these patterns, I concluded it was a Red-naped Sapsucker.

Continuing bird found today by LC on the CBC. Located in the large willows on the back side of the park, moved around a decent bit. Appears to be an adult female, based on the slight white in the chin and the lack of red beneath the eye. Yellow-bellied eliminated by lack of a strong black border to the red throat and a visible red nape. Appears to have no signs of hybridization with red-breasted or yellow-bellied. By far the rarest of the three "yellow-bellied" types in Marin, first chaseable bird in over 5 years.

Locality: Chance Road and Long Prairie Road
Observation Details: Continuing bird. Better view and photos during sun break. Appears to be a juvenile. Just getting dark feathers in black "shield" under red chin. Call matches RNSS. May not be pure RNSS but appears to have mostly characteristics of juvenile RNSS..changing species to RNSS based on input from several sources including: I don't see anything on this bird that suggests it is a hybrid. Generally, I would advocate for erring on the side of caution but there is no reason to suspect this bird is a hybrid. As Steve Shunk commented, westside reports of RNSA all too often turn out to be hybrids, not because it is so difficult to eliminate that possibility, but because folks just don't know what to look for when trying to eliminate the possibility of a hybrid. In my experience, RNSA X RBSA hybrids always show some red on the sides of the head and that red is typically bleeding through the white striping on the face, which absolutely guarantees it is a hybrid. I see no red anywhere on the head of this bird other than where it should be on a 'pure' RNSA, thus I would be entirely comfortable calling it one.  Dave Irons

*Early. Initially flushed out from deep within a pine and then relocated nearby in a juniper. Flushed again and only glimpsed briefly in flight. At this point, I was thinking it was a good candidate for a YBSA given its affinity for junipers/pines and the slightly early date (in my experience, YBSA tend to be furtive and stick to Scotch pines (?) and other similar tree species)). Decided to drive through town looking for it and narrowed in on a nonnative pine on the side of the road that looked good for a sapsucker. Sure enough, there it was attending sap wells against the bark, but the red nape, back pattern, etc indicate RNSA. Not conventional breeding habitat for the species, and given the sap wells on the pine, I wonder if it overwintered.

Locality: Golden Gate Park--Arboretum (San Francisco Botanical Garden)
Observation Details: Adult male, photos, continuing in "Cryptocarya alba" here: https://sfbg.gardenexplorer.org/taxon-3276.aspx.  One of two Red-naped Sapsuckers seen in the garden this winter.  Possibly the same returning male initially found by Alan Hopkins 11/13/21.   They are a scarce visitor to the West Coast from the interior mountains and Great Basin.  The nape, throat and back pattern are typical of this species. Note the even rows of small holes drilled in this tree by this bird so the sap bleeds. This species was split from the similar Yellow-bellied Sapsucker of Eastern North America in 1983.

Observation Details: Female sapsucker.  The chin and upper part of the throat was white with a band on red on the lower throat. There was a very small, but easily observable, red spot on the nape. The back is largely black with two fairly distinct lines of mottled feathers rather than the more widespread mottling as is seen in Yellow-bellied Sapsucker. The belly is very light yellow as is typical of many female Red-naped Sapsuckers.

Media notes: Bird #2
Observation Details: Apparently within range of variation for f rnsa.   Initially thought to be hybrids due to: Nicely intermediate with full black malar stripe (YBSA) and red patch on back of head (RNSA), and messy yellowish markings across mantle (not on restricted to two narrow rows as on pure RNSA). One had larger red nape than the other, and the mantle markings differed slightly; with one more broadly washed with yellow markings and one with more orderly (but messy) rows. Both in madrones at pullout at (31.5192502, -109.0045918).

extensive black on nape rules out red breasted.  Back pattern good for red naped sa   thin white line behind eye is good for red naped sa  black around red chin is good for Red naped sa but in some of the photos it apears to go completely around the red throat which is not good for adult red naped sa  I think this is a young male and some of the juvenile plumage is still present   If this is true more black should fill in under the red chin    as always if i got this wrong send me  a note  stevanbrad@gmail.com   Im going to ask one of the san diego best guys about this too  after typing this up I got the following note from Paul Lehman which some of you may like to read     Certainly a very large percent of the bird is a Red-naped. It is certainly not an obvious hybrid. Just that one little spot of red on the side of the face. Some folks think that is still OK for Red-naped, whereas a few think that might suggest some distant hybrid parentage. But it sure seems "close enough"! And I think that little red is really minimal, no matter what. A clear hybrid would show more red splotches in face AND would show red spilling down the breast, across the dark upper breast patch that it starting to grow in.

Observation Details: Found by Alan Hopkins yesterday. NP was on it in the previous reported location. Lines and colors in the head and face seem to match up well with RNSA. The age of the bird is in question - what seemed to be a brown wash resolved into more of a yellow in better light. On a softer note, the shelling or ticking on the sides of the breast is neatly developed and not muddy or incomplete. The white patch is well developed. And there is something going on in the coverts, there seems to be two different generations but woodpecker molt is all cattywampus. Peter showed up and we looked at it for a while, eliminated HY (though not 100%) and I didn't like adult and he suggested SY. If anyone managed to get photos of the primary coverts (tiny, dark feathers, just sticking out from the white patch, at the base of the primaries) please send these along, you can crop just to that area. Unfortunately they are often covered by the breast feathers. Short video of it preening: https://youtu.be/2pxrdQQftkg

An adult female with a much reduced amount of red in the throat. This might suggest that it is a hybrid with a Yellow-bellied Sapsucker, but all other plumage features are typical of a Red-naped with no sign of intermediacy. The back is largely black with two distinct lines of mottled feathers rather than the more widespread mottling as is seen in YBSA. The belly is very light yellow and the red spot on the nape also point to a typical RNSA.

First reported yesterday by John Bishop. I was in the area today and decided to stop by. The bird was found easily, once I arrived at the picnic area (coords of John’s checklist - dirt road requires high clearance vehicle) I accidentally flushed it from a snag and then was able to watch it for a while as it moved up a Ponderosa. I’ve seen many hybrid birds so far this year, and this is the first bird with RN features that didn’t scream hybrid. I may be missing some more intricate detail that would put it in the hybrid zone, but it looks good to me when compared to photos of RN. Red on head confined to cap, nape, and throat, with black under cap, white eyeline stripe, black cheek, and white stripe connecting to the red on the throat. Light belly with ‘blurry’ dark mottling that gives it a grayish look. Red throat met a black patch on the breast. Photos will be attached in a couple minutes, if there are any visible marks pointing to a hybrid please let me know! I’m always happy to learn. Apologies for poor photo quality.

This is an interesting and troublesome Sapsucker. My first impression in the field was a YBSA, because the red throat had a black border, yet it also had a tiny amount of red on the nape, which is possible in YBSA but more likely in a RNSA. Upon examination of the photo it shows the red partially bleeds into the black border, that and the small amount of red on the nape both support a hybrid YBSA X RNSA over a YBSA. Its also worth noting this is an immature bird,because of the lack of a black shield on the breast, and the advanced plumage is also indicative of RNSA genes in the bird. So why not just a RNSA? Well, this bird is a probably a male because it has an all red throat, and male RNSA should have no or very little black border on the red throat against the malar, also they usually have at least a little red on the cheek, and a larger red patch on the nape. I have read that some female RNSA can have an all red throat, but have yet to see any real evidence of that, all I have ever seen have a white chin, and most female RNSA have more red on the nape as well. So this is either a hybrid YBSA X RNSA or one of those rare female RNSA with an all red throat, and the later seems most likely.

Locality: Islay Creek Campground--Montana de Oro SP
Observation Details: Spotted in the southwest corner of loop one very still, perched high on a trunk under a canopy, maybe 15-20 feet off the ground. Bird was in a deciduous tree that has lots of fresh sapsucker holes and thick trunks. I called over a few birders to check out the sapsucker. Eventually, the bird preened then foraged along trunk. Adult male: red chin that wasn’t completely bordered with black. Red crown and nape separated by a black bar. Large white patch on wings, lots of white spots/speckling on dark back, barred underside and barred central tailfeathers. Observation Details: This sapsucker stood out to me because the black border seemed completely uninterrupted by the red in the throat. After reading some articles and deliberating, I've decided best odds are this is a female Red-naped Sapsucker with extensive red on the throat. In particular, specimen surveys published in Birding; Mldinow, Barry & Cox in Nov 2006 suggest this is more common than Yellow-bellied Sapsuckers with red napes. Also, the back pattern is better for Red-naped. I'll attach a poor digi-binned photo.  Seen across Parks Rd here: 33.897453, -117.952843

One female with lots of white on throat near post office; the bird was near 2 Red-breasted Sapsuckers, but I could not determine if any were paired with another. The second bird was the same female seen on 3 July on Willow Street. It was feeding young in a nest in a cottonwood with a Red-breasted Sapsucker. I determined that it was a female because it had a narrow row of white feathering at the base of the bill and slightly more white on the back than just two neat stripes, and the red on the nape were dull. I saw the Red-naped Sapsucker bring food to young in the nest five times during a 30-minute period before the Red-breasted fed them, and then the Red-breasted brought food twice in a 4-minute span. The nest was 20 feet up in a 35-foot tall cottonwood. The Red-breasted drummed once on a metal light.

Red nape.  **After long review of whether this is a YBSA, a RNSA, or a YBSA x RNSA hybrid, I am happy to call this a red-naped, simply because more features point towards that than a yellow-bellied.  A hybrid would be so hard to positively ID, so I am sticking with red-nape.

Observation Details: The bird was working in eucalyptus trees and live oak trees.  It was a sapsucker with a white streak from bill to nape, all red chin over black patch and then yellow belly, and a red nape.  I concluded that it was a male red-naped.  This is a continuing bird on the east side of the abandoned parking area in the center of the park.

Appeared to be an adult male. Mostly solid red crown (a few black feathers), and solid red throat. Fair bit of red in the nape, eliminating a "pure" Yellow-bellied. Pale tan-colored spotting on back forming two neat rows (creating essentially two wide streaks down the back) lacking the "messy" back pattern more typical of Yellow-bellied. A few red feathers on either side of the face may suggest some distant Red-breasted introgression (F2+ perhaps), but for most intents and purposes appears to be a pretty "pure" Red-naped. First seen in flight on the other side of the fence in the southeast corner of the property (near the trampoline), but eventually flew onto the property and was working the row of trees adjacent to the fence (where I was able to get quite a few close photos). I believe as many as two Red-naped have been reported here the past few weeks and it's been a good year for finding this species east of it's expected range in Texas this fall (likely birds moving out of burned areas in the Rockies and further West).

Observation Details: likely 2 different birds

Continuing male, present since fall 2021, and likely the same individual that has wintered at this location for the past few years.  Unlike the hybrid sapsucker that is hanging out in the same cluster of pepper trees, this bird has a broad black breast band below the completely red throat; a black bar separating the red crown from the red nape; a solidly black "mask" through the face, bordered above by a long, narrow white post-ocular stripe, and below by a long, broad, white mustache stripe, without red bleeding into either the black mask or the white facial stripes.  This individual seems to be more submissive in interactions with the hybrid bird, which seems to be more aggressive.  The hybrid seems to stick mainly to a couple of pepper trees directly up the bank above the golf course maintenance sheds, whereas the Red-naped seems to bury itself in the interior of the pepper trees a bit farther west (the same wooded patch where the Zonotrichia flock seems to shelter whenever flushed from the trail).  Photos to be uploaded later.

Back pattern good for red naped sa   thin white line behind eye is good for red naped sa  black around red chin is good for Red naped sa but in some of the photos it apears to go completely around the red throat which is not good for adult red naped sa  I think this is a young male and some of the juvenile plumage is still present   If this is true more black should fill in under the red chin    as always if i got this wrong send me  a note  stevanbrad@gmail.com   Im going to ask one of the san diego best guys about this too  after typing this up I got the following note from Paul Lehman which some of you may like to read     Certainly a very large percent of the bird is a Red-naped. It is certainly not an obvious hybrid. Just that one little spot of red on the side of the face. Some folks think that is still OK for Red-naped, whereas a few think that might suggest some distant hybrid parentage. But it sure seems "close enough"! And I think that little red is really minimal, no matter what. A clear hybrid would show more red splotches in face AND would show red spilling down the breast, across the dark upper breast patch that it starting to grow in.

I saw this bird fly into the tree across from my house at the corner of Cerro Romauldo and Santa Lucia. I'm tentatively calling it a pure Red-naped Sapsucker based on the following fieldmarks.  Limited facial red extending beyond the normal boundaries of RNSA fieldmarks, though the red on the head is more extensive than might be expected in RNSA.  Two distinct vertical columns of white extending down the back of the bird, typical in RNSA.  Unmarked black in the breast, typical of RNSA. A hybrid would likely show some red.  However, the black band in the hindcrown of the bird is broken by red coloration, suggesting that there may be some RBSA blood in this bird. A typical RNSA would show a complete black band unbroken by red.  Perhaps this bird is a hyrbid, has some RBSA blood in its lineage, or just shows more wear on its feathers. Any input is very welcome.

Observation Details: Continuing bird. Local rarity. Red crown and red on the nape. Some reduced red feathering on the throat.  Pale yellow wash on belly. The rest is mostly black and white. Photos to follow.
I got clear views in the same location as previously located. Between volleyball court and pavilion. Photos to a be added later.

Based on comparative photos this was a continuing bird initially reported at this location by Tom Edell and Mike Bush on 12/4/20. Bird was an adult male with extensive, all red throat and chin; black border on head separating red on nape from red crown, and yellowish wash below breast-band.

Observation Details: Seen in tipu trees here: (33.7965320, -118.1379000). (Note: there’s also a conifer with sapsucker holes by the baseball backstop.) Photo.
Continuing female first reported by Tony Kurz a few weeks ago. Photos.

An immature sapsucker, with black chest crescent not yet developed, although adult head pattern (mostly?) acquired. White chin and fore throat with red lower throat as on adult female Red-naped Sapsucker, but minimal to no red in nape (at least yet). Third photo shows some possible hint at red in nape. Back pattern seems better for Red-naped than Yellow-bellied. White facial stripes seem narrow in last/8th photo, although quite broad in the 7th photo.

Adult female found earlier by Gary Lester. (41.1352060, -124.1601396). On the left hand side the bird is making square sap wells I the first small alder branches on the left side the tree. Photos.
